 ```md\\n   Because v1 has no Forge-specific public redaction pass, Forge must only render records returned by a `but-agentlog` public/read projection whose redaction guarantees are explicit. Forge must not read or render raw internal records directly.\\n   ```\\n\\n3. **Branch fallback can accidentally surface unrelated sessions.**  \\n   Branch names are w\n[TRUNCATED]\npublic GitHub PR URL. The doc mentions bare caches and locks, but should also call out fetch/resource limits.  \\n   See [agent-trail.md](</Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/agent-trail.md:297>).\\n\\n   Suggested wording:\\n   ```md\\n   V1 should only accept recognized GitHub PR URL shapes, never arbitrary git URLs. Repository initialization and metadata fetches need timeouts, size limits, per-repo locking, rate limits, and cleanup. The server must not run hooks, recurse submodules, fetch LFS, or execute repository content.\\n   ```\\n\\n5. **Forks need an explicit hard stop.**  \\n   The doc says forks are unsupported, but branch fallback could still accidentally use a head branch name from a fork. Make the behavior concrete.  \\n   See [agent-trail.md](</Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 Active/agent-session-capture/agent-trail.md:68>).\\n\\n   Suggested wording:\\n   ```md\\n   If a PR head repository is different from the base repository, v1 should not use branch fallback. It should return an unsupported-fork state unless review-target metadata is available from the base repository metadata ref.\\n   ```\\n\\n6. **Snapshots need indexing/cache posture.**  \\n   Even for public repos, Agent Trail makes obscure metadata easy to browse. That is amplification. I’d add `noindex` for v1 unless the goal is public SEO.  \\n   Suggested wording:\\n   ```md\\n   Public v1 snapshots should be treated as public-but-not-promoted: stable enough to share, but served with `noindex` until the publication model is mature.\\n   ```\\n\\n**Must-Ask Before Building**\\n\\n1. Is a publicly fetchable `refs/meta/main` enough consent to render Agent Trail publicly, or do we need an explicit publish marker per PR/review?\\n\\n2. For branch-only matches, are we okay showing them automatically as weaker evidence, or should v1 only show review-target matches unless the user explicitly asks for broader matches?\\n\\nEverything else can wait. These two shape the first implementation in ways that are annoying to reverse later.\"}}","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T14:46:40.769Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}